  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The garden is the first impression buyers form of a home, and in Brisbane it is also a genuine part of the lifestyle a buyer is paying for. A well-presented front garden signals that the house has been cared for. A tired one plants a doubt that everything else might be tired too. This is not about winning a horticultural prize. It is about giving buyers no reason to discount.</p>

      <p>The tricky part is that garden work can become a money pit. Sellers who throw themselves into a full landscape redesign four weeks before listing almost never recover the cost, and the work rarely looks settled enough by the first open home to be credible. The goal is targeted preparation, not transformation. Spend where buyers actually look, leave the rest, and keep everything tidy for the duration of the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What buyers actually register</h2>
      <p>Watch a buyer arrive at an open home and you will see the same pattern repeat. They take in the street, the front boundary, the approach to the front door, and the overall sense of order. If any of those is visibly neglected, they walk in with their guard up. If all four look considered, they walk in relaxed and ready to like the house. That psychological starting point is worth more than any individual garden bed.</p>

      <p>Buyers also read the back garden carefully, especially families and anyone planning to entertain. They want to see a usable outdoor space, a reasonable ratio of lawn to garden, and evidence the space has been enjoyed rather than abandoned. Photographs of the back garden sell the lifestyle promise that the floor plan alone cannot.</p>

      <p>What buyers rarely notice are the details gardeners obsess over. The specific cultivar of a hedge, the exact trim line on a topiary, the state of a side bed that nobody walks past. Energy spent on those details is energy not spent on the areas that move the needle.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The high-return jobs</h2>
      <p>Six jobs reliably punch above their weight, and together they cost a fraction of what a full landscape refresh would. Start here and stop when the garden reads as tidy, cared for, and coherent.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pressure wash hard surfaces.</strong> Driveways, paths, patios, pool surrounds, and retaining walls go grey over time in the Brisbane climate. A pressure wash strips away mould, grime, and algae in a single afternoon and takes years off the property visually. On older Queenslanders in Camp Hill, Morningside, and Hawthorne, this single job often produces the most dramatic before-and-after of any preparation work.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Cut the lawn short and edge it cleanly.</strong> A lawn with a crisp edge along every path and garden bed reads as deliberately maintained. A lawn without edging reads as weeks overdue for attention, even if it was mowed yesterday. Edge the day before every open home for four weeks, and mow the day before the photography shoot.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Mulch every visible garden bed.</strong> Fresh hardwood or tea tree mulch unifies beds that otherwise look patchy and tired. It hides bare soil, suppresses weeds through the campaign, and gives the whole garden a finished look for a few hundred dollars. Skip coloured or dyed mulches, which photograph oddly and feel artificial.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Prune aggressively along sight lines.</strong> Any branch, shrub, or tree limb that blocks the view of the house from the street, darkens a window, or overhangs the front path needs to come back. Buyers want to see the house. Mature planting that has grown over the facade dates a home by a decade even when the facade itself is in excellent condition.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Replace or fill anything obviously dead.</strong> A single dead shrub in a bed of living ones anchors the eye and tells buyers the garden is being neglected. Pull it out, and either replant with a mature specimen from a local nursery or top up the bed with mulch so the gap is not obvious. Do not leave a stump, a dead trunk, or a sun-bleached container through the campaign.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Add seasonal colour near the front door.</strong> A single large pot of healthy annuals or a cluster of three matching pots at the front entrance draws the eye, reads as welcoming, and signals that someone is actively caring for the home. This is the cheapest and most reliable lift you can buy. Expect to spend under $300 for a result that carries every photograph and every open home.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The jobs that rarely return their cost</h2>
      <p>Some garden investments feel like they should pay off but consistently do not. A full turf replacement on a front lawn is a common one. New turf needs weeks to knit together before it can be photographed credibly, and buyers cannot tell a three-month-old lawn from a three-year-old one. Unless the existing lawn has died back to bare earth, aerate, fertilise, and water for four weeks instead. You will get eighty per cent of the benefit for five per cent of the cost.</p>

      <p>Major structural changes, like rebuilding a retaining wall or re-laying a driveway, almost never return their cost in a sale campaign. Buyers will either not notice or not pay a premium for work they assume they could have chosen differently. If the existing structure is safe and tidy, leave it alone and direct those funds toward the six high-return jobs above.</p>

      <p>Full landscape redesigns before sale are the clearest trap. The design takes weeks to specify, the installation takes weeks to complete, and the planting takes months to settle. The work looks raw in photographs, the budget balloons beyond the original quote, and the return in sale price rarely exceeds what the same money would have produced spent on styling the interiors and updating the kitchen splashback.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Trees, hedges, and the boundary</h2>
      <p>Mature trees on a Brisbane inner east property are almost always an asset. They suggest an established home, they provide shade for the roof and garden, and they frame the house in photographs. The exceptions are trees that are visibly unhealthy, trees that drop fruit or debris on the neighbour, and trees that block every window on the street-facing side of the house. Engage an arborist to assess any tree you are uncertain about, rather than making a decision yourself in the two weeks before listing.</p>

      <p>Hedges and boundary planting should be trimmed to a consistent line and a consistent height. An overgrown front hedge closes the property off from the street and blocks the view of the house. A hedge that has been brought back to a clean line opens the property up and invites buyers in. Engage a professional hedge trimmer if your hedge is more than head height. The result will be cleaner than anything you can achieve with a consumer trimmer on a ladder.</p>

      <p>The boundary fence is worth walking with a fresh eye. Any panel that leans, sags, or has broken palings needs to be repaired or replaced. A tired boundary fence is one of the easiest things for a buyer to point to when negotiating the price down. A repaired one removes that argument entirely.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The pool surround and outdoor living areas</h2>
      <p>Homes with a pool or a deck have an additional presentation layer to manage. The pool itself needs to be crystal clear with a clean waterline for every open home and every photograph. A cloudy pool or a ring of grime above the waterline tells buyers the pool is not being maintained, which they assume extends to the rest of the property.</p>

      <p>The pool surround, whether paved, tiled, or decked, should be scrubbed free of mould and algae. Pressure-wash the surface, reapply any timber oil or sealer that is flaking, and replace any obviously damaged pavers or boards. Remove the pool cleaner from the water during open homes and photography, and tuck pool equipment out of sight.</p>

      <p>Deck and paved entertaining areas benefit from the same treatment. A clean, oiled deck with a styled outdoor setting photographs as a lifestyle feature. A tired deck with a rusted barbecue photographs as a maintenance liability. If the deck is in reasonable condition, a single weekend of oil or stain will lift it more than any other outdoor spend.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Timing and maintenance through the campaign</h2>
      <p>Start the heavier garden work four weeks before listing. That gives pruning time to settle, mulch time to weather into the beds, and any newly planted specimens time to establish. Book the pressure wash and hedge trim for the week before photography, when the work is at its freshest. Book a final tidy the day before each open home so the lawn edges, garden beds, and outdoor areas look newly maintained every time buyers arrive.</p>

      <p>Maintenance through the campaign matters more than sellers expect. A garden that looked perfect on day one can easily slip by day twenty-one. Set a standing weekly appointment with a gardener for the duration of the campaign if you are not confident you will keep it tidy yourself. The cost is minor. The alternative is a property that looks less fresh at every subsequent open home, and a buyer pool that is actively comparing the photographs to what they see in person.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A realistic budget</h2>
      <p>For a standard inner Brisbane home on a 405 to 607 square metre block, a sensible garden preparation budget lands between $800 and $2,500 depending on how much needs doing. Pressure washing, mulching, edging, pruning, and a round of potted colour can be done well within that range and will carry the campaign. Spending materially more than that rarely pays off, and spending less usually means something important is being skipped.</p>

      <p>A professional garden styling consultation is a useful one-hour investment before you decide where to spend. A good local gardener or landscaper can walk the property, nominate the jobs that will produce the largest visual lift, and flag the jobs you should not bother with. An hour of that advice is often worth more than the next five hours of your own unguided weeding.</p>

